to which members express their identification with the organization, and whether the audience is public or local, author Craig R. Scott describes collectives as residing in "regions" that range from transparent to shaded, from shadowed to dark. Taking a closer look at groups like EarthFirst!, the Church of Scientology, Alcoholics Anonymous, the KKK, Skull and Bones, U.S. special mission units, men's bathhouses, and various terrorist organizations, this book draws attention to shaded, shadowed, and dark collectives as important organizations in the contemporary landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCommunication in organizations. 0aComparative organization. 0aSecrecyxSocial aspects. 4aanonymity. 4aaudience. 4acommunication. 4adark organizations. 4ahidden organizations. 4aidentification. 4aidentity. 4asecrecy. 4ashaded organizations. 4ashadowed organizations. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Organizational Behavior.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804785631zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804785631423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804785631.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles